## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests examined · 9 Critical findings · 1 Medium**

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called, giving you ~95% line coverage, but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if the production code is completely broken — which is exactly why bugs escape to production.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

All 10 tests follow the same pattern: call the method, optionally check `IsNotNull`, move on. This is the single root cause of your production bugs.

**6 of 10 tests have zero assertions at all:**

| Test Method | Line | What's Missing |
|---|---|---|
| `AddProduct_Works` | 17–21 | Never checks the product was stored |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` | 33–36 | Never checks the price actually changed |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` | 39–43 | Never checks the product was removed |
| `GetProductCount_Works` | 64–66 | Never checks the count value |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | 69–74 | Never checks prices were discounted |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` | 85–88 | Never checks a product was imported |

**Fix for each — add a real assertion after the act:**

```csharp
// AddProduct_Works → AddProduct_ProductIsRetrievable
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);

// UpdatePrice_Works → UpdatePrice_PriceIsChanged
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);

// RemoveProduct_Works → RemoveProduct_ProductIsGone
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));

// GetProductCount_Works → GetProductCount_ReturnsCorrectCount
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();
Assert.AreEqual(1, count);

// ApplyBulkDiscount_Works → ApplyBulkDiscount_ReducesPrices
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
var discounted = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, discounted?.Price); // 9.99 * 0.90

// ImportFromCsv_Works → ImportFromCsv_ProductIsStored
_catalog.ImportFromCsv("SKU-001,Widget,9.99");
var imported = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(imported);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", imported.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, imported.Price);
```

#### 2. Weak Assertions — `IsNotNull` as Sole Verification (3 tests)

| Test Method | Line | Problem |
|---|---|---|
| `GetProduct_Works` | 28 | `IsNotNull` — never checks Sku, Name, or Price |
| `SearchProducts_Works` | 51 | `IsNotNull` — never checks result count or contents |
| `GetAllProducts_Works` | 59 | `IsNotNull` — never checks the list has any items |

`IsNotNull` only proves the method returned *something*. It would pass if `GetProduct` returned a completely wrong product.

**Fixes:**

```csharp
// GetProduct_Works → GetProduct_ReturnsCorrectProduct
var result = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(result);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", result.Sku);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", result.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, result.Price);

// SearchProducts_Works → Search_MatchingQuery_ReturnsMatchingProducts
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.AreEqual(1, results.Count);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", results[0].Sku);

// GetAllProducts_Works → GetAll_AfterAdd_ReturnsAddedProduct
var all = _catalog.GetAll();
Assert.AreEqual(1, all.Count);
```

